## Best Practices

### DO ✅

```ruby
# Use appropriate column types
t.string :email         # Short text
t.text :body           # Long text
t.decimal :price       # Money
t.boolean :published   # True/false

# Add NOT NULL constraints
t.string :title, null: false

# Set default values
t.boolean :active, default: true
t.integer :views_count, default: 0

# Always add timestamps
t.timestamps

# Index foreign keys
add_index :articles, :user_id

# Index frequently queried columns
add_index :articles, :status
add_index :articles, :published_at

# Add unique constraints for unique data
add_index :users, :email, unique: true

# Use foreign key constraints
t.references :user, foreign_key: true

# Name join tables alphabetically
article_tags  # Not tag_articles
```

### DON'T ❌

```ruby
# Don't use string for large text
t.string :body  # Use t.text instead

# Don't forget NOT NULL for required fields
t.string :email  # Add null: false

# Don't use float for money
t.float :price  # Use t.decimal instead

# Don't forget indexes on foreign keys
# Always add: add_index :articles, :user_id

# Don't create redundant columns
# Bad: user_first_name (duplicate of users.first_name)
# Good: Just use user.first_name via association

# Don't use generic names
t.string :name      # Bad (name of what?)
t.string :user_name # Good (specific)

# Don't store calculated values that can be computed
# Bad: t.integer :comments_count
# Good: article.comments.count (or counter_cache)
```

